main_data <- read.csv("A1_data.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = TRUE)

A random sample of 900 observations was taken from the data to work with for the project. A seed of “8” was used and then the sample was sorted in ascending order based on the “ID” variable. Index “1”, “100”, “200” and “500” were then produced to cross-check SUNLearn to verify the integrity of the data

#correction of data
new_test_data = filter(test_data,DURATION > 0)

#recalculation of correlation
round(cor(new_test_data$DURATION,new_test_data$AMOUNT),digits = 3)
## [1] 0.629

In the plot above we can see that there is a usual observation (duration = -5). It is impossible to have a negative duration, as that would imply that you needed to pay your loan 5 years before the loan even started. I have there for removed the observation and recalculated the correlation between DURATION and AMOUNT to be 0.629

The average loan for the different categories seems to be relatively grouped into 3 different ranges. “Household content”, “education” and “repairs” all being ± R80 000 and both “business” and “Cars” being ± R120 000. “other” is the final range but despite being the smallest category (10 loans) it has the largest average loan amount of ± R200 000.

The first range of ± R80 000 appears to be inline with the types of objects that every person will need regardless of their social class and therefore it is on average a lot lower amounts. The second range of ± R120 000 is the more middle class seeing as not everyone will have the financial ability to buy a car for themselves or open their own business. The third range of ± R200 000 appears to be objects that are not being financed regularly enough to have their own category and are thereby likely to be things only a very small amount of people can afford.

It is however only speculative as these variables by themselves are not enough to make a prediction with accuracy.

When analyzing the summary statistic it can clearly be seen that youth does indeed have a lower mean amount for the loans (R95,512 against R 102,428 ) as well as a lower median (R66,800 against R71,900). This combined with the fact that the youth have a lower max amount of (R482,700 against R567,500), can it be clearly stated that youth tend to borrow smaller amounts of money compared to ages 30 plus. By looking at the box chart and the scatter plot we can see that the older group contains more outliers which suggest that the older clients tend to be more sporadic. The scatter plot appears to show a negative correlation between age and the loan amount, thereby suggesting the older you are the less you will borrow. This is misleading however once we dig deeper. When we calculate the correlation we get 0.091 for youth and -0.031 for the older clients. These values are so close to zero that they are considered to be to statistically insignificant to overrule any information we gained from the means and median values. Therefore no mathematically concrete conclusion can be drawn about the correlation between age and the amount of the loan but based on the summary statistic it can be stated that younger people do in fact tend to borrow lower amounts, with older clients having more variability in the amount they borrow.

In all other cases, they appear to be identical. This proves the fact that there are other variables at play.

Question 12

By doing further analysis I identified the following variables based on the graphs created and the difference in the status ratio.

Important factors:

The amount the client received as well the duration in which the loan will be paid back in seems to have the largest effect on weather a client’s status will be seen as “good” or “bad” seeing as the difference in ratios was the largest. The client’s current balance also seems to have a large effect as a clear correlation can be seen as well. The credit history of the client is also identified as being among the most important variables.

Variable Conclusion
Amount: The higher the amount a client borrows, the more likely they are to have a “bad” status.
Duration: The longer the client’s loan period is, the more likely they are to have a “bad” status.
Current Balance: The lower a client’s current balance is, the more likely the are to have a “bad” status. If the account is overdrawn (current balance is negative), the client has the lowest chance of having a “good” status. However if the client does not currently have a bank account at this bank, they are overwhelmingly more likely to receive a “good” status.
Credit History: Counter-intuitively the worse the client’s credit history the more likely they are to be given a “good” status. Further analysis of more variables will be required in order to determine as to why this is the case.
Secondary factors:

I identified the client’s age as well as weather they have external loans to have an affected but the difference in ratio of the status is lees than the important factors above.

Variable Conclusion
Age: There seems to be a relationship between age and status with middle-aged clients (35 - 60) being more likely to receive a “good” status on average. This can be due to older people on average are living stable lives and have a larger current balance. There this variable is categorized as a secondary factor.
External loans: while not a large difference in ratio, there is a visible difference in the likelihood that a person with no external loans will receive a “good” status more than those with external loans. This difference is marginal however so therefore this variable is also categorized as a secondary factor.
Possible factors:

These variables showed a difference in the ratio of the status but the difference was either very small or the is no clear relationship between the variables.

Variable Conclusion
PERC: The PERC (customer’s loan installment relative to the customer’s income) does have a difference in ratio, with higher relative percentages being more likely to receive a “good” status. This difference is so small however that there is no clear evidence that this variable has an effect on the status of the client
Savings: Clients with lower savings seem to be more likely to receive a “good” status. This variable also has a small difference in ratios combined with the fact that people with no account are in the middle of “low” and “high” savings accounts, can no clear conclusion be made as to its importance to the status of the client
